# Never Rebase

**CRITICAL RULE: NEVER use git rebase in this project.**

## Why
- Rebasing rewrites commit history, which can cause issues with shared branches
- Rebasing can create duplicate commits when pushing to remotes
- Rebasing makes it harder to track the actual history of changes
- This project uses merge-based workflow for safety and clarity

## What to Do Instead

### When pulling changes:
- Use `git pull` (which merges by default)
- Or explicitly: `git pull --no-rebase`
- Or: `git fetch` followed by `git merge`

### When branches diverge:
- Always use merge, never rebase
- Example: `git pull origin main` (creates a merge commit)
- If you see "divergent branches", use merge to reconcile

### If you accidentally rebased:
- Do NOT push
- Use `git reflog` to find the commit before rebase
- Reset to that commit: `git reset --hard <commit-hash>`
- Then use merge instead

## Commands to Avoid
- ❌ `git pull --rebase`
- ❌ `git rebase`
- ❌ `git rebase -i` (interactive rebase)
- ❌ `git pull --rebase` in any form

## Commands to Use
- ✅ `git pull` (default merge)
- ✅ `git pull --no-rebase`
- ✅ `git fetch` then `git merge`
- ✅ `git merge <branch>` for merging branches

## Exception
There are NO exceptions to this rule. Always use merge, never rebase.
